<Document>
<name>Luang Prabang to Vientiane</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Luang Prabang to Vientiane</h2><p><i>Laos · Route 13, Luang Prabang to Vientiane via Vang Vieng</i></p><p><b>410 km across northern Laos — UNESCO temple town, karst peaks, Mekong tributaries, the relaxed capital.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>241 km (150 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>8–10 hrs straight; ideally 2–3 days with Vang Vieng stop</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–February (dry, cool); avoid burning season (Mar–Apr) and heaviest rains (Aug–Sep)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Mountain road washouts in rainy season; truck convoys on slow climbs; livestock; some sections still being upgraded; the section north of Vang Vieng was the focus of past banditry concerns — now stable but check current advice</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>417</td></tr></table><hr><p>Route 13 is Laos's spinal road — the country has only a handful of paved highways, and this is the main one. Luang Prabang at the northern end is a UNESCO World Heritage former royal capital where the morning alms-round of orange-robed monks happens every dawn. The road climbs to Phou Khoun on a mountain ridge then drops to Vang Vieng, set among karst peaks above the Nam Song River. Vang Vieng was infamous for backpacker tubing parties in the 2000s; that's been cleaned up, and the surrounding country (caves, lagoons, balloon rides at sunrise) is quietly back to being one of Laos's best landscapes. Vientiane, the capital, is a low-slung Mekong-side city of French colonial architecture and gold-stupa wats — the most relaxed national capital in Asia.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Luang Prabang</b> — UNESCO old town at the confluence of the Mekong and Nam Khan. Climb Mount Phousi for sunset over the Mekong. Wat Xieng Thong (1559) is the masterpiece of Lao temple architecture. Morning alms-round at dawn (be respectful — observe quietly, don't crowd the monks).</li><li><b>Kuang Si Falls (spur from Luang Prabang)</b> — 30 km southwest. Multi-tier limestone falls cascading into turquoise pools you can swim in. Black bear sanctuary at the entrance (rescued from bile farms).</li><li><b>Phou Khoun</b> — Hill-junction village at 1,250 m — last stop on the Plain of Jars detour east. The Plain (a 90 km detour) holds thousands of Iron Age stone jars whose purpose is still debated.</li><li><b>Vang Vieng</b> — Karst peaks rising from rice paddies above the Nam Song. Hot-air balloon flights at sunrise (book ahead). Blue Lagoon swimming holes (multiple, all called Blue Lagoon — go to #2 or #3 to escape the crowds at #1). Caves: Tham Phu Kham.</li><li><b>Vientiane</b> — That Luang (1566) is the national stupa — gold, three-tiered, the symbol on Lao currency. Patuxai is a 1960s Lao take on the Arc de Triomphe ('the vertical runway' — built with US aid concrete intended for an airport). Mekong sunset from the riverbank esplanade.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
